= El pleno de la puerta

The reform will be law by December and the Party must walk into that month with a position, which means the war happens now, internally, in a hall with bad acoustics: the ortodoxos with fifty years of receipts proving the state's doors are traps; the renovadores with a single unanswerable question — *then what, compañeros, was the plan?*; the nueva izquierda torn between its coordinadoras and its curiosity. Every current has its veto points memorized. December will be a stampede or a decision depending on what the leadership does with these weeks.

- @preparar_pleno: Do it the hard way: two months of cell-by-cell debate, the vote counted before it is cast — arrive at December already decided.
- @dejar_diciembre: Let December decide itself. Forcing the debate early spends authority the leadership may want for the vote itself.

@preparar_pleno
go-to: post_event
choose-if: political_capital >= 5
unavailable-subtitle: Pre-clearing a decision this size takes authority the leadership does not currently hold.
on-arrival: political_capital -= 5; lfope_preclear = 1; unity += 3; des_ortodoxos -= 4; des_nueva -= 4

It is the least glamorous work in politics and the most decisive: the position papers circulated to every cell, the objections collected and answered in writing, the ortodoxos given their full hour in every local and their dissent minuted with respect. By late November the Party knows its own mind — knows it cell by cell, with numbers. Whatever December brings, it will not bring a stampede: the house has already argued itself to a decision, which is the only kind that holds.

@dejar_diciembre
go-to: post_event
on-arrival: political_capital += 1

The leadership husbands its authority for the vote itself. Defensible — Decembers have been survived before — but the cells spend the autumn arguing without materials, the corridors fill with versions, and the decision, when it comes, will land on a party that has been quarreling instead of deliberating. The difference will be paid in unity, whichever way the vote goes.
